## Direct formatting
see also [Formatting](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-business-designer-user-guide-create-and-edit-templates-short-instruction-guide#formatting)

To format elements, you can edit all the available options on the right panel below the palette in the *Style &amp; Properties *section.

> Note

*To combine several formats and assign them together in one single step, you can create style sheets - see Chapter *[Create style sheets](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-business-designer-user-guide-formats-and-style-sheets#create-style-sheets).

In order to perform formatting directly on the element, the element must be selected. The desired formatting can be set on the right side under *Style &amp; Properties*.

Example: for a text containing block, the attributes font color red, font size 19pt and style bold are set:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

> Note

*Numeric values must be entered together with a unit of measurement such as "pt" (point) or "mm". If no value is entered, the value is ignored. Confirm the entry with the Enter key or click in the next input field. Allowed measurements are: cm, mm, in, pt (point), pc, px.*

You can **remove formats **by deleting the entered values, by removing them with the X symbol or by switching them off with the respective button (e.g. italics or paragraph alignment). Another option is you can search for the corresponding attribute in the category *Advanced *and delete it there (e.g. Font color under *Advanced *&gt; *Colors*, attribute "color").

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

If you want to format only parts of a text, you must select the desired text part in the design view and then set the format attributes. This automatically places the text part in a separate text element, otherwise the different formatting is not possible.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

**Frame**: Frames are usually set for tables - for setting frames see chapter [Border](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-business-designer-user-guide-tables#border). Note that for other elements it makes a difference on which level the frame is set. E.g. a frame on a text element: the text itself or each line of the text is surrounded by the frame. A frame on a block: the paragraph is surrounded by the frame.

> Note

*If the same frame properties are defined for two consecutive blocks, the two blocks are surrounded by two separate frames. To set a frame surrounding several blocks instead, e.g. a frame around several paragraphs, put these blocks into a container element and set the frame for the container.*

Often you can choose to apply formatting to a block or the containing element. To keep an overview, make sure to set formats as systematically or uniformly as possible, i.e. either always directly on the elements or as recommended always on the respective block.

## Inheritance of formats
Make sure to set formats on the appropriate layer. Text formats are inherited by default in the element hierarchy if possible.

Formats you set e.g. for a block will be applied to all elements that are inside that block, if applicable to the respective element type. In the same way, attributes are set e.g. for a table, they are applied to all subordinate columns and rows.

You can combine several blocks in a single container element - this gives you a central element for format attributes, since the child elements of the container adopt its attributes.

However, on a subordinate level additional attributes can of course be set at any time. If different attributes are set, they have priority over the attributes inherited from above.

## Create style sheets
It has proven to be a good idea to create style sheets instead of performing formatting directly on individual elements. Meaning that a format or a combination of formats is saved under a name and then applied to elements - to change the properties of all elements, only the format template has to be changed. This facilitates changes and supports consistent formatting.

You can open the Style Sheet Manager by clicking the *Styles *button in the left toolbar.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

For the ease of use styles are always divided into groups. Therefore, newly created documents already have an empty style group "Unnamed_Group_1". It can be renamed (Edit symbol on the group name).

> Note

*The names of styles and style groups/sets cant contain spaces.*

Create style sheet:

- Click the diamond symbol on the group name.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- Enter a name for the new style and confirm with Enter or by clicking on the check mark.

- Click on the new style sheet. Now you can set any property and formatting on the right side, just like it is with direct formatting.

The set properties are listed under the style name. To change individual properties, use the pencil symbol next to the respective line.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

This opens the area on the right under the format attributes in which the property was set. You can delete a property from the style sheet by clicking the recycle bin icon.

## Apply style sheets
To apply a style to an element, select the element (in the Design view) and then choose the style from *Style &amp; Properties *&gt; *Styles*. In the drop-down you can see the list of existing groups including the containing style sheets.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

If an element has been formatted with a style sheet, you can see it on the left side of the outline. A small diamond icon is now displayed on top of the element icon.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

The style sheet is inherited by its child elements. For example, if you place a style template on a block containing three text elements, these texts are formatted accordingly.

> Note

*Always pay attention to the element hierarchy and the display of the diamond symbol in the outline.*

On the right side under *Style &amp; Properties *&gt; *Styles*, inherited styles and styles are not displayed - e.g. the style set on a block is only visible if the block is selected, but not if the contained text element is selected.

To remove an assigned style, use the small X symbol in the selection field or the eraser symbol to the right.

> Note

*The formats set with style sheets often cannot be displayed in the editor. Always take a look at the PDF output document to check formatting.*

If the directly set properties differ from the style sheet properties, the directly set properties apply. The original style wont be changed by this.

> Note

*If you delete a style template in the Style Manager that is still in use, the corresponding styles are automatically removed from the affected elements.*

## Create style sheet collection
You can use style sheets across files when you save them in a style sheet collection. The collection is an ITX file in which you only create style sheets - the rest can be left empty.

To do this, create a new collection file of the type "Style Package".

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

In this file, you then create as many styles as you like in any number of groups, as described in [Create style sheets](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-business-designer-user-guide-formats-and-style-sheets#create-style-sheets).

## Use styles from the collection
In the template in which you want to use the styles from the collection, you must first **include the collection file**: To do this, go to the Style Template Manager, use the folder icon in the upper right corner and select the collection file.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

> Note

*The style sheet collection must be placed in the same repository as your template file.*

The groups and style sheets are imported and displayed below the local groups/style sheets. The imported groups are given the suffix "(external)" in their names, so they can be distinguished from the local styles.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

You can now **assign **the **external styles **to elements in the same way that you assign local styles. Group names are also marked with "(external)" in the selection list.

Management of external style sheets:

Of course you cannot change external styles in your template, but only in the original collection file itself. With the folder icon (on the group) you can open the collection file directly to apply changes.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

If you want to remove the included styles, delete any of the external groups (recycle bin icon) - this will unmount the entire style collection, and all style groups in the same collection file will be removed (i.e. you cannot remove individual style groups). All references to the external styles will be removed.

> Note

*Make sure that there are no naming conflicts between local and external styles. If there are naming conflicts, the local style has precedence and if there is no local style (conflict between two external styles) the deepest external style will be used.*
